b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p1_chem_symbols" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title> Chemical Symbols </title>\n        <objref idref="chemical_symbols"/>\n    </head>\n    <body>\n        <p> Previously we discussed elements and the periodic table. Elements are represented by a\n            chemical symbol. A chemical symbol is an abbreviation that we use to indicate an element\n            or an atom of an element. For example, the symbol for mercury is Hg. We use the same\n            symbol to indicate one atom of mercury (microscopic domain) or to label a container of\n            many atoms of the element mercury (macroscopic domain). </p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/mercury.jpg" width="400"\n            alt="A jar labeled \xe2\x80\x9cH g\xe2\x80\x9d is shown with a small amount of liquid mercury in it.">\n            <caption>The symbol Hg represents the element mercury regardless of the amount; it could\n                represent one atom of mercury or a large amount of mercury.</caption>\n        </image>\n        <p> The symbols of all elements are listed on the periodic table of elements. </p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/periodic_table.jpg" width="700" alt="The Periodic Table of Elements is shown. The 18 columns are labeled \xe2\x80\x9cGroup\xe2\x80\x9d and the 7 rows are labeled \xe2\x80\x9cPeriod.\xe2\x80\x9d Below the table to the right is a box labeled \xe2\x80\x9cColor Code\xe2\x80\x9d with different colors for metals, metalloids, and nonmetals, as well as solids, liquids, and gases. To the left of this box is an enlarged picture of the upper-left most box on the table. The number 1 is in its upper-left hand corner and is labeled \xe2\x80\x9cAtomic number.\xe2\x80\x9d The letter \xe2\x80\x9cH\xe2\x80\x9d is in the middle in red indicating that it is a gas. It is labeled \xe2\x80\x9cSymbol.\xe2\x80\x9d Below that is the number 1.008 which is labeled \xe2\x80\x9cAtomic Mass.\xe2\x80\x9d Below that is the word hydrogen which is labeled \xe2\x80\x9cname.\xe2\x80\x9d The color of the box indicates that it is a nonmetal. Each element will be described in this order: atomic number; name; symbol; whether it is a metal, metalloid, or nonmetal; whether it is a solid, liquid, or gas; and atomic mass. Beginning at the top left of the table, or period 1, group 1, is a box containing \xe2\x80\x9c1; hydrogen; H; nonmetal; gas; and 1.008.\xe2\x80\x9d There is only one other element box in period 1, group 18, which contains \xe2\x80\x9c2; helium; H e; nonmetal; gas; and 4.003.\xe2\x80\x9d Period 2, group 1 contains \xe2\x80\x9c3; lithium; L i; metal; solid; and 6.94\xe2\x80\x9d Group 2 contains \xe2\x80\x9c4; beryllium; B e; metal; solid; and 9.012.\xe2\x80\x9d Groups 3 through 12 are skipped and group 13 contains \xe2\x80\x9c5; boron; B; metalloid; solid; 10.81.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 14 contains \xe2\x80\x9c6; carbon; C; nonmetal; solid; and 12.01.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 15 contains \xe2\x80\x9c7; nitrogen; N; nonmetal; gas; and 14.01.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 16 contains \xe2\x80\x9c8; oxygen; O; nonmetal; gas; and 16.00.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 17 contains \xe2\x80\x9c9; fluorine; F; nonmetal; gas; and 19.00.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 18 contains \xe2\x80\x9c10; neon; N e; nonmetal; gas; and 20.18.\xe2\x80\x9d Period 3, group 1 contains \xe2\x80\x9c11; sodium; N a; metal; solid; and 22.99.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 2 contains \xe2\x80\x9c12; magnesium; M g; metal; solid; and 24.31.\xe2\x80\x9d Groups 3 through 12 are skipped again in period 3 and group 13 con