l; solid; and 204.4.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 14 contains \xe2\x80\x9c82; lead; P b; metal; solid; and 207.2.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 15 contains \xe2\x80\x9c83; bismuth; B i; metal; solid; and 209.0.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 16 contains \xe2\x80\x9c84; polonium; P o; metal; solid; and 209.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 17 contains \xe2\x80\x9c85; astatine; A t; metalloid; solid; and 210.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 18 contains \xe2\x80\x9c86; radon; R n; nonmetal; gas; and 222.\xe2\x80\x9d Period 7, group 1 contains \xe2\x80\x9c87; francium; F r; metal; solid; and 223.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 2 contains \xe2\x80\x9c88; radium; R a; metal; solid; and 226.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 3 breaks the pattern much like what occurs in period 6. A large arrow points from the box in period 7, group 3 to a special row containing the elements with atomic numbers ranging from 89-103, just below the row which contains atomic numbers 57-71. In sequential order by atomic number, the first box in this row contains \xe2\x80\x9c89; actinium; A c; metal; solid; and 227.\xe2\x80\x9d To its right, the next is \xe2\x80\x9c90; thorium; T h; metal; solid; and 232.0.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c91; protactinium; P a; metal; solid; and 231.0.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c92; uranium; U; metal; solid; and 238.0.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c93; neptunium; N p; metal; solid; and N p.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c94; plutonium; P u; metal; solid; and 244.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c95; americium; A m; metal; solid; and 243.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c96; curium; C m; metal; solid; and 247.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c97; berkelium; B k; metal; solid; and 247.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c98; californium; C f; metal; solid; and 251.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c99; einsteinium; E s; metal; solid; and 252.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c100; fermium; F m; metal; solid; and 257.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c101; mendelevium; M d; metal; solid; and 258.\xe2\x80\x9d Next is \xe2\x80\x9c102; nobelium; N o; metal; solid; and 259.\xe2\x80\x9d The last in this special row is \xe2\x80\x9c103; lawrencium; L r; metal; solid; and 262.\xe2\x80\x9d Continuing in period 7, group 4 contains \xe2\x80\x9c104; rutherfordium; R f; metal; solid; and 267.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 5 contains \xe2\x80\x9c105; dubnium; D b; metal; solid; and 270.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 6 contains \xe2\x80\x9c106; seaborgium; S g; metal; solid; and 271.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 7 contains \xe2\x80\x9c107; bohrium; B h; metal; solid; and 270.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 8 contains \xe2\x80\x9c108; hassium; H s; metal; solid; and 277.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 9 contains \xe2\x80\x9c109; meitnerium; M t; not indicated; solid; and 276.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 10 contains \xe2\x80\x9c110; darmstadtium; D s; not indicated; solid; and 281.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 11 contains \xe2\x80\x9c111; roentgenium; R g; not indicated; solid; and 282.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 12 contains \xe2\x80\x9c112; copernicium; C n; metal; liquid; and 285.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 13 contains \xe2\x80\x9c113; ununtrium; U u t; not indicated; solid; and 285.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 14 contains \xe2\x80\x9c114; flerovium; F l; not indicated; solid; and 289.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 15 contains \xe2\x80\x9c115; ununpentium; U u p; not indicated; solid; and 288.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 16 contains \xe2\x80\x9c116; livermorium; L v; not indicated; solid; and 293.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 17 contains \xe2\x80\x9c117; ununseptium; U u s; not indicated; solid; and 294.\xe2\x80\x9d Group 18 contains \xe2\x80\x9c118; ununoctium; U u o; not indicated; solid; and 294.\xe2\x80\x9d"> </image>\n        <p> Notice that the atomic number for each element is listed on the periodic table and that\n            the elements are arranged in order atomic number. We will discuss the periodic table in\n            more detail later in this course. </p>\n          <wb:inline idref="atoms_periodic_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n\n        <section>\n            <title>Isotopes</title>\n            <body>\n                <p> During the early 1900s, scientists identified several substances that appeared\n                    to be new elements, isolating them from radioactive ores. For example, a \xe2\x80\x9cnew\n                    element\xe2\x80\x9d produced by the radioactive decay of thorium was initially given the\n                    name mesothorium. However, a more detailed analysis showed that mesothorium was\n                    chemically identical to radium (another decay product), despite having a\n                    different atomic mass. This result, along with similar findings for other\n                    elements, led the English chemist Frederick Soddy to realize that an element\n                    could have types of atoms with different masses that were chemically\n                    indistinguishable. These different types are called <extra><anchor>isotopes</anchor><meaning><material><p>Atoms of the same element that has different masses due to different numbers of neutrons.</p></material></meaning></extra>\xe2\x80\x94atoms of the same\n                    element that differ in mass. Soddy was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in\n                    1921 for this discovery. Later it was determined that the cause of the different\n                    masses between isotopes of the same element is different numbers of\n                    neutrons.</p>\n                <image src="../webcontent/isotopes.png" width="600"\n                    alt="Diagram of 2 atoms. The one on the left has 3 electrons, 3 protons, and 3 neutrons. The one on the right has 3 electrons, 3 protons, and 4 neutrons.">\n                    <caption>These diagrams represents isotopes of the same element. They have the\n                        same number of protons, but different numbers of neutrons.</caption>\n                </image>\n                 <wb:inline idref="isotope_diagram_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n                <p>The symbol for a specific isotope of any element is written by placing the mass\n                    number as a superscript to the left of the element symbol. The atomic number is\n                    sometimes written as a subscript preceding the symbol, but since this number\n                    defines the element\xe2\x80\x99s identity, as does its symbol, it is often omitted. For\n                    example, magnesium exists as a mixture of three isotopes, each with an atomic\n                    number of 12 and with mass numbers of 24, 25, and 26, respectively. These\n                    isotopes can be identified as <sup>24</sup>Mg, <sup>25</sup>Mg, and <sup>26</sup>Mg. These isotope symbols are\n                    read as \xe2\x80\x9celement, mass number\xe2\x80\x9d and can be symbolized consistent with this\n                    reading. For instance, <sup>24</sup>Mg is read as \xe2\x80\x9cmagnesium 24,\xe2\x80\x9d and can be written as\n                    \xe2\x80\x9cmagnesium-24\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9cMg-24.\xe2\x80\x9d <sup>25</sup>Mg is read as \xe2\x80\x9cmagnesium 25,\xe2\x80\x9d and can be written as\n                    \xe2\x80\x9cmagnesium-25\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9cMg-25.\xe2\x80\x9d All magnesium atoms have 12 protons in their nucleus.\n                    They differ only because a <sup>24</sup>Mg atom has 12 neutrons in its nucleus, a <sup>25</sup>Mg atom\n                    has 13 neutrons, and a <sup>26</sup>Mg has 14 neutrons.</p>\n\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <section><title>Different Ways to Represent Isotopes</title>\n        <body>\n            <image src="../webcontent/Mg_24.png" width="600"\n                alt="Three different ways to represent an isotope of magnesium-24.">\n                <caption>Three different ways to represent magnesium-24.  </caption>\n            </image>\n            <image src="../webcontent/Mg_isotopes.png" width="600"\n                alt="Symbols for 3 isotopes of magnesium. The one on the left has a mass number of 24 and an atomic number of 12 and indicates that it has 12 protons and 12 neutrons. The one in the center has a mass number of 25 and an atomic number of 12 and indicates that it has 12 protons and 13 neutrons. The one on the right has a mass number of 26 and an atomic number of 12 and indicates that it has 12 protons and 14 neutrons.">\n                <caption>Symbols representing the three isotopes of magnesium</caption>\n            </image>\n              <wb:inline idref="isotopes_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n            \n        </body></section>\n\n\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'